<@U026PHQ3J> I’m taking a look at one of the tickets Lynsey mentioned earlier and I was wondering if you could give me any clues on how to increase the parallax effect on cropped images in Moments. I’ve been looking at the `doInBackground` method in `ImageCropActivity.ImageCropSaveTask` and `recomputeTransformMatrices()` in `MomentsBlurDimGLRender` but I’m a little lost on how to actually make the image pan to the right (beyond the area specified in crop) when the user swipes right on the home screen.
for the record!
i actually initially made it crop wider but bonnie didn’t like it
Hahaha why am i not surprised
so basically if you look in ImageCropActivity

you need to trace back from the width that its using in the line ```            Bitmap temp = MomentsImageUtility
                    .cropAndSaveMomentsImage(getApplicationContext(), mImage, leftX, 0,
                            leftX + resultWidth, mNativeImageHeight);```
Just to clarify, is the width determined by `leftX + resultWidth`?
kind of
most of that code can remain untouched IF
those lines set the dimensions of the overlay that we drag around
note that `overlayWidth` is the result of `targetAspect` and the height of the overlay (which is related to the height of the native image that we’re cropping)
`                float targetAspect = (mScreenWidth * 1.15f) / (float) mScreenHeight;`
which boils down to (1.15 * screen width)
which is what eventually ends up being scaled up to be the width of the post-cropped image
Gotcha
(note that same computation is used in the AsyncTask that actually crops the photo)
so first:
replace the 1.15f with a constant
(its not cause i’m sloppy and i never thought we’d actually release this)
then mess with that constant (don’t go too far over 1.8 or 2.0)
(or it will get odd)
that should widen out the overlay and the cropped image
it WILL LOOK STUPID on portrait images
so get ready for that
Hahah alright. Thanks for the help!!
remember:
first step: replace 1.15f in both places with a constant
call it aspect_modifier or parallax_modifier
(its saying that the destination image should be 15% wider than the screen size, btw)
That makes sense
